DENGUE/DHF UPDATE 2008 (05)
*************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

In this week's update:
[1] Paraguay
[2] Brazil
[3] Peru
[4] New Caledonia
[5] Philippines (Cebu)

******
[1] Paraguay
Date: Wed 30 Jan 2008
Source: BBC News [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7217071.stm>


There are fears of complications after last year's [2007] outbreak. A
health alert has been declared in Paraguay in a bid to stop a new
outbreak of dengue fever.

Health workers have detected some 150 suspected cases of the
mosquito-borne disease so far this year [2008].

A senior Paraguayan official said there was concern that neighbouring
Brazil had also seen a recent rise in dengue and some dozen cases of
yellow fever.

Last year [2007], 17 people died from dengue fever in Paraguay, and
the authorities were criticised for not acting sooner. "Dengue is
defeated in the streets. We can fight the mosquitoes, chiefly by
getting rid of stagnant pools of water," said Paraguayan President
Nicanor Duarte as the health alert was declared.

His government was accused of missing warning signs in January a year
ago [2007] and failing to tackle the disease properly. A total of
some 27 000 cases were registered during 2007, 17 of them fatal.

The Paraguayan Health Minister, Oscar Martinez, said the latest
suspected cases were being analysed. "We have 11 confirmed cases
after the initial tests, and so we will wait a fortnight to carry out
a 2nd test to confirm whether it is dengue," he told the BBC. "We're
asking people to support us and help us get rid of places where
mosquitoes can breed," he said.

Officials say their concern is that people who were infected last
year [2007] might be more susceptible to more serious forms of the
disease. There is a much greater risk of dengue haemorrhagic fever or
dengue shock syndrome when a person has immunity to one of the other
types of dengue virus as a result of previous infection.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[An article posted by ProMED-PORT published in ANSA Latina (on 29 Jan
2008, in Portuguese,
<http://www.ansa.it/ansalatinabr/notizie/fdg/200801291304303150/200801291304303150.html>)
indicated that the 150 suspected (11 confirmed) dengue cases were
mainly from the departments (state or province equivalent) of Alto
Parana, on the border with Brazil, and Central, neighboring the
capital Asuncion. A map of Paraguay showing its departments can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/paraguay_pol98.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

******
[2] Brazil
Date: Wed 30 Jan 2008
Source: O Povo Online [In Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.opovo.com.br/opovo/brasil/762596.html>


There were 41 neurological dengue cases [that] were recorded in the
country last year [2007], according to the figures published by the
Ministry of Health and released yesterday [29 Jan 2007] in Brazilia.
Sao Paulo state, which registered the largest dengue epidemic in its
history, led with the largest number of notifications [neurologic
dengue cases], with 9, followed by Para (6), Piaui (6) e Parana (4),
Alagoas (3), Maranhao (2) and Rio Grande do Norte (2). One case each
was registered in Amazonas, Amapa, Paraiba, Pernambuco, Bahia,
Espirito Santo, Minas, Rio de Janeiro and Mato Grosso do Sul.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT <promed@promedmail.org>

[The classification of "neurologic dengue" does not exist; dengue can
have neurologic complications, such as encephalitis and peripheral
neuropathies. This report of neurological complications is nothing
exceptional, since there is the increase in dengue cases in Brazil,
complications will be more visible. - Mod.LJS, trans. Mod.TY]

[A map of Brazil showing the states can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/brazil.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

******
[3] Peru
Date: January 2008
Source: Bol. Epidemiol. (Lima) No. 2 [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY]
<http://www.oge.sld.pe/boletines/2008/02.pdf>


In the 2nd epidemiological week [SE 2; 2nd week of January 2008], the
country-wide notification of classic dengue cases was 254, of which 6
have been confirmed by the [Direccion General de Epidemiologia,
Ministerio de Salud (DIRESA) -- in English: Office of the Director of
Epidemiology of the Ministry of Health] Madre de Dios laboratories.
[Of these], 78 percent are from DIRESA Loreto (55 percent) and
Ucayali (23 percent) [regions]. Up to SE 02, 11 health directorates
have [provided] notification of locally acquired dengue cases. There
has been a continuous Dengue outbreak in the Loreto DIRESA during the
1st 2 weeks of 2008. Jaen and Madre de Dios, having been in an
epidemic [situation] during the 1st week [of January 2008], have had
a reduction [in the number of] cases. Until now, there have been no
cases of DHF.

Up to the 2nd epidemiological week, 33 districts have [given]
notification of dengue cases. The districts reporting 52 percent of
the cases in the country are: Belem, Iquitos, San Juan Bautista and
Punchana of the Loreto DIRESA.

[The report goes on to give a detailed breakdown of dengue cases by
district within the DIRESAs. - Mod.TY]

A rapid evaluation of _Aedes_ [dengue virus vector mosquito]
infestation in December 2007 gave indices of 15 percent and 6.7
percent in these 2 districts. [It is not clear from this report
whether these indices are percentages of houses/buildings infested
with _Aedes_, as seems likely, or the proportion of suitable
containers having larvae or pupae. - Mod.TY]

