[4] New Caledonia
Date: Fri 1 Feb 2008
Source: Marianas Variety [edited]
<http://www.mvariety.com/?module=displaystory&story_id=6029&format=html>


Health authorities in New Caledonia are considering the current
health situation as a pre-epidemic stage with regards to the
hemorrhagic, mosquito-transmitted dengue fever, with 15 new cases
detected since the beginning of this month [January 2008] here in the
capital Noumea and its immediate suburbs.

Authorities say the January [2008] figures, provided by the
Noumea-based Institut Pasteur, are of particular concern, since the
whole figure for 2007 was 47 cases reported.

Most of the new reported cases were detected in the Greater Noumea
area, especially in the suburban town of Dumbea, New Caledonia's
health and social department pointed out.

The alarm comes as New Caledonia and its greater region are facing
severe weather conditions characterized by high humidity and heavy
rains, which are triggering factors for mosquito-borne diseases such
as dengue fever, malaria, typhoid, dysentery or leptospirosis.

New Caledonia's health and prevention department has for the past few
weeks stepped up its prevention and awareness campaign against the
potentially deadly virus, mainly because of the heavy rains and the
hot and humid conditions currently affecting New Caledonia.

Health authorities are therefore considering that, at present, even
though there is no epidemic as yet, the health risk for dengue fever
is at a maximum.

As part of the prevention campaign, Noumea's health and hygiene
services have also deployed since the beginning of this month
[February 2008] a team of a dozen of officers, whose main task is to
visit house and property owners and convince them to clean any
potential mosquito breeding site, such as still water contained in
old tires and plant pots or any bushy area on their compound that
could also become a nest for mosquito larvae.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[A map of Oceania showing the location of New Caledonia in the South
Pacific can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/australia/oceania_ref_2007.pdf>.
- Mod.TY]

