[5] Philippines (Cebu)
Date: Thu 31 Jan 2008
Source: Wow Philippines [edited]
<http://visayas.wowphilippines.com/cebu/2008/01/31/doh-7-central-visayas-hits-highest-fatality-rate-for-dengue-nationwide/>


Cebu City has the highest fatality rate of DHF, as health officials
prepare to set up a plan along with other stakeholders for the
simultaneous nationwide launching of the intensified campaign drive
against dengue set next month [February 2008]. Department of Health
(DOH-7) Regional Director Dr. Susana Madarieta, during the Kapihan sa
PIA this morning [31 Jan 2008] on dengue updates, said that out of
the total 6640 recorded dengue cases in Central Visayas last year
[2007], 148 of the victims died of the disease, constituting a 2.2
percent mortality rate.

Out of the top 10 areas in the region that have a high incidence of
dengue cases, 7 of these areas belong to Cebu Province, Madarieta said.

Cebu City tops the list of areas with a high incidence rate of
dengue, with over 1600 cases, followed by Tagbilaran City, while the
3rd spot is Mandaue City with 355 cases and 14 recorded deaths, it is reported.

Other areas in Cebu having a high incidence of dengue include
Minglanilla, Talisay City, San Fernando, City of Naga and Toledo
City, while the other 3 areas are in Bohol and included Dauis and Jagna.

DOH-7 Chief on Communicable Diseases Dr. Jocelyn Abellana revealed
that most of the victims were as young as 4-months-old with the
oldest at 68-years-old, while the majority belonged to the lower
socio-economic class, as the dengue virus [and dengue virus vector
_Aedes_ mosquitoes. - Mod.TY] thrives more in densely populated areas.

Madarieta also admitted that Region 7 ranks 3rd on the most number of
morbidity cases of dengue next to the National Capital Region and Region 3.

From 2006-2007, the number of dengue cases ballooned to 109 percent
higher than the previous year, as there were only 3172 cases of
dengue recorded in 2006, with 76 deaths, although the mortality rate
was then 2.4 percent, Madarieta further said.

Because of the rising incidence of dengue cases in the country, the
DOH has stepped up an intensified campaign drive against dengue with
a simultaneous nationwide launching scheduled on 21 Feb [2008], which
will be a whole-year round advocacy.

Madarieta said that previously, they only launched the dengue
advocacy drive during the start of the rainy season, but with the
growing incidence of dengue cases, the intensified advocacy will be a
whole-year round campaign.

The _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, the carrier of the dengue virus, is a
daytime vector that thrives in clean stagnant water, and health
officials once again stressed the importance of cleaning one's
surroundings and destroying the possible breeding sites of the
dengue-carrier vector. Madarieta added that they will seek the
involvement of other stakeholders in the community, such as the local
government units, religious sector and the barangay captains to help
the government in its whole-year campaign drive against dengue.

[Byline: Glenrose]

--
